  "prompt": "How often should employees get a performance review?",
  "response": "The frequency of performance reviews can vary depending on the organization, industry, and company culture. However, here are some common approaches:\n\n1. Annual Performance Reviews\n- Most traditional approach\n- Typically conducted once per year\n- Comprehensive evaluation of employee performance\n\n2. Bi-Annual Reviews\n- Conducted twice per year\n- Allows for more frequent feedback and goal tracking\n- Can help identify and address issues more quickly\n\n3. Quarterly Reviews\n- More frequent check-ins\n- Provides regular opportunities for feedback and adjustment\n- Often used in fast-paced or rapidly changing environments\n\n4. Continuous Performance Management\n- Ongoing feedback and discussions\n- Regular one-on-one meetings\n- Less formal, more real-time assessment\n\n5. 360-Degree Reviews\n- Feedback from multiple sources (managers, peers, subordinates)\n- Can be done annually or less frequently\n\nBest practices recommend:\n- At minimum, an annual formal review\n- Regular informal check-ins and feedback\n- Tailored approach based on employee role and organizational needs\n\nThe trend is moving towards more frequent, less formal performance discussions that provide continuous feedback and support employee development.",
